    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-07-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-07-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="520"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d520">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">812.113/10572</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to President
                            <persName type="to">Hoover</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-07-18">July 18,
                            1929</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. President</hi>: I transmit herewith for your
                    signature, a Presidential Proclamation<note n="91" xml:id="d520fn91">Same as
                        signed proclamation, <ref target="#pg_432">p. 432</ref>.</note> lifting the
                    embargo which has been in force since January 7, 1924, on the shipment of arms
                    to Mexico. This action is taken pursuant to a request from the Mexican
                    Government. Both Ambassador Morrow and I approve of the proposed course of
                    action. The Presidential election in Mexico takes place in November and the new
                    President will presumably be inducted into office on February 5, 1930. If our
                    action is delayed until the election or thereafter, it would undoubtedly be
                    susceptible to mis-interpretation. I therefore recommend that the Proclamation
                    be issued without delay.</p>
                <p>I also transmit for your approval a release<note n="92" xml:id="d520fn92">Not
                        printed.</note> which I propose to issue to the press as soon as the signed
                    Proclamation is returned by you.</p>
                <p>I enclose for your reference a copy of President Coolidge’s Proclamation of
                    January 7, 1924<note n="93" xml:id="d520fn93">
                        <ref target="frus1924v02#pg_428">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1924, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 428</ref>.</note> which it is proposed
                    now to revoke. I also transmit herewith a copy of President Wilson’s
                    Proclamation of February 3, 1914<note n="94" xml:id="d520fn94">
                        <ref target="frus1914#pg_447">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, 1914, p. 447</ref>.</note> which lifted
                    the embargo imposed during President Taft’s administration.<note n="95"
                        xml:id="d520fn95">Proclamation of March 14, 1912, <ref
                            target="frus1912#pg_745">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, 1912, p. 745</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Henry L. Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
